  "prompt": "What causes a sonic boom?",
  "response": "A sonic boom is caused when an object travels faster than the speed of sound, which is approximately 343 meters per second (1,235 kilometers per hour) in air at sea level. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Sound waves normally spread out in all directions from their source\n\n2. When an object moves slower than the speed of sound, sound waves can spread out ahead of the object\n\n3. When an object travels at or near the speed of sound (supersonic speed), sound waves cannot \"get out of the way\" fast enough\n\n4. This creates a compression of sound waves, building up intense pressure\n\n5. When the object breaks the sound barrier, it creates a sudden, sharp shock wave\n\n6. This shock wave is what we hear as a loud \"boom\" or thunderclap\n\nCommon examples of objects creating sonic booms include:\n- Supersonic aircraft like military jets\n- Space shuttles during re-entry\n- Bullets fired from certain high-powered rifles\n- Whips being cracked (which can create a small sonic boom)\n\nThe intensity of a sonic boom depends on factors like the object's size, shape, speed, and altitude. The boom is typically loudest directly underneath the object's path.",
